Introduction & Background

Time series analysis is a major branch in statistics that mainly focuses on analyzing data set to study the characteristics of the data and extract meaningful statistics in order to predict future values of the series.

In this project, we have applied two different ways to explore the stock price modeling and prediction. First we will go through several traditional time series modeling and prediction methods and apply them to the stock price analysis. Further, instead of using the statistical modeling methods, we will apply the machine learning technique and do the modeling and prediction based on the historical stock data. After comparison, we will show that the machine learning method is also a powerful tool for financial system analysis.

Time Series Modeling

Decomposition model

So far, our analysis has been restricted to plotting the data and looking for features such as trend and seasonal variation Now we want to consider some approaches for modeling time series. The first is based on an assumption that there is a fixed seasonal pattern about a trend.We can estimate the trend by local averaging of the deseasonalised data, and this is implemented by the R function decompose().

Many series are dominated by a trend and/or seasonal effects, so the models in this section are based on these components. A simple additive decomposition model is given by:

\[x[t]= m[t] + s[t] + R[t]\]

where x[t] is the time series process at time t, m[t] is the trend, s[t] is the seasonal effect, and R[t] is the error term which is a sequence of usually correlated random variables with mean zero. The goal is to find a decomposition such that R[t] is a stationary time series.

If the seasonal effect tends to increase as the trend increases, a multiplicative model may be more appropriate:

\[x[t]= m[t].s[t] + R[t]\]

Empirical experience says that taking logarithms is beneficial for such data. Also, some basic math shows that this brings us back to the additive case:

\[log(x[t])= m'[t] + s'[t] + R'[t]\]

First let us try the additive model:

AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_add <- decompose(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, type="additive")
plot(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_add, col="blue")

Then let us try the multiplicative model, and its corresponding logarithms:

AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_mult <- decompose(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, type = "mult")
plot(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_mult, col="green")

AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_log <- decompose(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.log.ts, type="additive")
plot(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_log, col='red')

Note that the last additive model is based on the logarithmic transformation of multiplicative model.

We can compare the additive model and multiplicative model. In this example, the multiplicative model would seem more appropriate than the additive model because the variance of the original series and trend increase with time (see the random component we can find that the multi model has smaller value).

We can also put the decomposition parts together and compare them to the real observed data. Below we use multiplicative model as an example:

clr <- c("green3","red3","blue3")
Real_Data <- AAPL_monthly_last_five_data$Adj.Close
Trend <- AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_mult$trend
Seasonal <- AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_mult$seasonal
Mult_cbind <- cbind(Trend, Trend * Seasonal, Real_Data)
colnames(Mult_cbind) <- c("Trend","Trend*Seasonal","Real_Data")
ts.plot(Mult_cbind, lty = 1:2, col=clr, ylab="Adj.Close price")
legend("topleft", lty=1, col=clr, legend=colnames(Mult_cbind))

Once we have identified any trend and seasonal effects, we can get the random component. But the random component is not necessarily well modelled by independent random variables. In many cases, consecutive variables will be correlated. If we identify such correlations, we can improve our forecasts.

Consider a time series model that is stationary in the mean and the variance. The variables may be correlated, and the model is second-order stationary if the correlation between variables depends only on the number of time steps separating them. The number of time steps between the variables is known as the lag. A correlation of a variable with itself at different times is known as autocorrelation or serial correlation.

In R, an autocovariance function (acvf), \(\gamma\)[k], as a function of the lag k is defined as:

\[\gamma[k] = E[(x[t] - \mu)(x[t+k] - \mu)]\]

And The lag k autocorrelation function (acf), \(\rho\)[k], is defined by: \[\rho[k]=\gamma[k]/(\sigma^2)\]

By default, the acf function produces a plot of sample acf r[k] against k, which is called the correlogram.

The main use of the correlogram is to detect autocorrelations in the time series after we have removed an estimate of the trend and seasonal variation.

We can apply the acf() function to the above three decomposition models (including the logarithmic transformation of multiplicative model):

acf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_add$random,na.action=na.omit, lag.max = 20) # correlogram for additive model

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
acf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_mult$random,na.action=na.omit, lag.max = 20) # correlogram for mult model
acf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.decom_log$random,na.action=na.omit, lag.max = 20) # correlogram for log model

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

From the plots we can see the logarithmic transformation of multiplicative model is slightly better than the other two models, but none of all three models performs very well ( there is significant autocorrelation at some lags), hence we may need further modeling.

Also we can plot the correlogram of the original data. the autocorrelations, which are large and positive due to similar values in the series occurring close together in time.

acf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1), lag.max = 20) # just show the correlogram of the the original data

Linear Regression model

Trends in time series can be classified as stochastic or deterministic. when we have some plausible physical explanation for a trend we will usually wish to model it in some deterministic manner. Deterministic trends and seasonal variation can be modelled using regression. Time series regression usually differs from a standard regression analysis because the residuals form a time series and therefore tend to be serially correlated.

First let us introduce the linear regression models.

A model for a time series {x[t] : t = 1, . . . n} is linear if it can be expressed as

\[x[t] = \alpha0 + \alpha1.u[1,t] + \alpha2.u[2,t] + . . . + \alpha m.u[m,t] + z[t]\]

where \(u[i,t]\) is the value of the ith predictor (or explanatory) variable at time \(t (i = 1, . . . ,m; t = 1, . . . , n)\), \(z[t]\) is the error at time t, and \(\alpha0\), \(\alpha1\), . . . , \(\alpha m\) are model parameters.

First we can fit a simple linear regression model for the AAPL stock price from (2010,01) to (2014,12)

AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm = lm(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts ~ time(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts))
coef(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm)
##                          (Intercept) time(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts) 
##                         -26665.22705                             13.28163
plot(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, type="o", ylab="close price",col="red", xlab="Time", main="simple linear regression model")
abline(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm, col="blue")

After fitting a regression model, we should consider various diagnostic plots. In the case of time series regression, an important diagnostic plot is the correlogram of the residuals:

hist(resid(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm)) #should be normal for a good fit

acf(resid(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm), na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1),lag.max = 20)

AIC(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm)
## [1] 458.6778

From the acf() plot, it shows that the simple linear regression model is not very good as the correlogram has some significant autocorrelated points.

As time series are observations measured sequentially in time, seasonal effects are often present in the data, especially annual cycles caused directly or indirectly by the Earth’s movement around the Sun. Since this reason, we should conside the linear model with seasonal variables

A seasonal indicator model for a time series \({x[t] : t = 1, . . . , n}\) containing s seasons and a trend \(m[t]\) is given by

\[x[t]= m[t] + s[t] + R[t]\]

We have already seen this model in the additive decomposition model. Below we can apply the linear model with seasonal variables to our data:

Seas = cycle(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts)
# This gives the positions in the cycle of each obsv.
Time = time(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts)
# This creates the vector of times at which AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts was sampled
AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.sv.lm = lm(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts~0+Time+factor(Seas))
# This fit AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts to the linear model with seasonal variables

Note a zero is used within the formula to ensure that the model does not have an intercept. Now we can take a look at the AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.sv.lm:

Random Walk model

So far, we have considered two approaches for modelling time series. The first is based on an assumption that there is a fixed seasonal pattern about a trend, and we use the decomposition model. Besides, we also do some regression to fit the time series model. When we fit mathematical models to time series data, we refer to the discrepancies between the fitted values, calculated from the model, and the data as a residual error series.

Since we judge a model to be a good fit if its residual error series appears to be a realisation of independent random variables, it seems natural to build models up from a model of independent random variation, known as discrete white noise.

Before we start the modeling, let us introduce what is white noise. A time series {w[t] : t = 1, 2, . . . , n} is discrete white noise (DWN) if the variables w1,w2, . . .,wn are independent and identically distributed with a mean of zero. This implies that the variables all have the same variance \(\sigma^2\) and \(Cor(w[i],w[j]) = 0\) for all \(i != j\).

After knowing the white noise, we can introduce the random walk model.

Let us first introduce the random wlak definition.

Let {x[t]} be a time series. Then {x[t]} is a random walk if

\[x[t] = x[t-1] + w[t]\]

where {w[t]} is a white noise series. Substituting \(x[t-1] = x[t-2]+w[t-1]\) and then substituting for \(x[t-2]\), followed by \(x[t-3]\) and so on gives:

\[x[t] = w[t] + w[t-1] + w[t-2] + . . .\]

In practice, the series will start at some timet = 1. Hence,

\[x[t] = w[1] + w[2] + . . . + w[t]\]

A random walk often provides a good fit to data with stochastic trends, although even better fits are usually obtained from more general model formulations, such as the ARIMA models.

We can try to apply the first-order differences of a random walk to model our stock price time series as following:

AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.diff <- diff(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, lag=1)
plot(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.diff, ylab='Adj.Close',main="random walk time series model for 2010-2014", col="blue")

acf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.diff, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1), lag.max = 20)

From the correlogram plot, we can see it is better than the previous decomposition model (as there are less significant points). However, it is still not very good. The reason is that it doesn’t follow a strict random walk as there is also an increase trend.

Instead of just a random walk model, it should be a random walk with some drift. The random walk model can be adapted to allow for this by including a drift parameter \(\sigma\).

\[x[t]=x[t-1] + \sigma + w[t]\]

We can explore the drift effect as below:

mean(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.diff) 
## [1] 1.406503
mean(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.diff) + c(-2,2)*sd(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.diff)/sqrt(length(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.diff))
## [1] 0.1652882 2.6477184

Since the confidence interval does not include zero, we have evidence of positive drift over this period.

Auto-Regressive Model \(AR(p)\)

The most natural formulation of a time series model is a linear regression approach on the past instances, i.e. a regression on the series itself. This coined the term autoregressive. In practice, such models prove to be very important; they are the most popular way of describing time series.

The series \({x[t]}\) is an autoregressive process of order \(p\), abbreviated to \(AR(p)\), if

\[x[t] = \alpha1.x[t-1] + \alpha2.x[t-2] + . . . + \alpha p.x[t-p] + w[t]\]

where \({w[t]}\) is white noise and the \(\alpha i\) are the model parameters with \(\alpha p != 0\) for an order \(p\) process.

A very important point is \(AR( p)\) models must only be fitted to stationary time series. Any potential trends and/or seasonal effects need to be removed first.

Fitting an \(AR( p)\) model to data involves three main steps. First, the model and its order need to be identified. Second, the model parameters need to be estimated and third, the quality of the fitted model needs to be verified by residual analysis.

The model identification step first requires verifying that the data show properties which make it plausible that they were generated from an \(AR( p)\) process. In particular, the time series we are aiming to model needs to be stationary, show an ACF with approximately exponentially decaying envelope and a PACF with a recognizable cut-off at some lag p smaller than about 5-10. (Note thattThe partial autocorrelation \(pacf()\) at lag k is the correlation that results after removing the effect of any correlations due to the terms at shorter lags. For example, the partial autocorrelation of an \(AR(1)\) process will be zero for all lags greater than 1.)

The choice of the model order p then relies on the analysis of the sample PACF. Following the paradigm of parameter parsimony, we would first try the simplest model that seems plausible. This means choosing the smallest p at which we suspect a cut-off, i.e. the smallest after which none, or only few and weakly significant partial autocorrelations follow.

Let us do the \(acf()\) and \(pacf()\) plot for our data.

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
acf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1),lag.max = 20)
pacf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1),lag.max = 20)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

Form the \(pacf()\) plot, we should try with the smallest candidate first, which is \(p=1\). Also we can try some higher order, like \(p=12\). We need to note that lower order is better for modeling and prediction as the more parameters the greater noise that can be introduced into the model and hence standard deviation.

For the Parameter Estimation, we can try two different Auto-Regressive methods: \(ar.ols()\) and \(ar.burg()\)

# ar.ols() method for AR(1)
AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.ar.ols <- ar.ols(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, aic=F, intercept=F, order=1)
AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.ar.ols
## 
## Call:
## ar.ols(x = AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, aic = F, order.max = 1,     intercept = F)
## 
## Coefficients:
##      1

When comparing different models, a simple approach is to plot the original series along with the fitted model values. A good model yields residuals that resemble a White Noise process.

plot(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts, main ='AAPL AR analysis for 2010-2014', xlab="Time", ylab="Adj.Close price", type="o", col="blue")

It is easy to see that the Normal QQ-Plot also shows the \(AP(12)\) model is better. However, we still need to note that the higher order is not good for prediction as it considers too much parameters (kind like the “overfitting” problem in machine learning).

Moving average models \(MA(q)\)

Before we introduce the ARIMA model, it would be better to introduce the moving average model \(MA(q)\).

A time series model \({x[t]}\) is strictly stationary if the joint statistical distribution of \(x[t1] , . . . , x[tn]\) is the same as the joint distribution of \(x[t1+m], . . . , x[tn+m]\) for all \(t1, . . . , tn\) and \(m\), so that the distribution is unchanged after an arbitrary time shift. If a series is not strictly stationary but the mean and variance are constant in time and the autocovariance only depends on the lag, then the series is called second-order stationary.

A moving average (MA) process of order \(q\) is a linear combination of the current white noise term and the \(q\) most recent past white noise terms and is defined by

\[x[t] = w[t] + \beta 1.w[t-1] + . . . + \beta q.w[t-q]\]

where \({w[t]}\) is white noise with zero mean and variance \(\sigma^2[w]\).

An \(MA(q)\) model can be fitted to data in R using the arima function with the order function parameter set to \(c(0,0,q)\). Below is the example application of \(MA(1)\) on our data.

AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm.ma <- arima(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm$residuals, order=c(0,0,1), method = "CSS") # Use the CSS approach for the parameter estimation
AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm.ma
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm$residuals, order = c(0, 0, 1), method = "CSS")
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ma1  intercept
##       0.9439     0.0669
## s.e.  0.0857     1.5937
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 39.89:  part log likelihood = -195.72
acf(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts.lm.ma$res[-1], lag.max = 20)

From the result we can see sigma^2 estimated as 39.89, which is very big and the acf() is also not good, the model is bad, as the model is not stationary

ARIMA(p,d,q) Model

Knowing the \(AR(p)\) model and \(MA(q)\) model, we can easily understand the \(ARMA(p,q)\) model.

A time series \({x[t]}\) follows an autoregressive moving average (ARMA) process of order \((p,q)\), denoted \(ARMA(p,q)\), when

\[x[t] = \alpha 1. x[t-1] + \alpha 2.x[t-2] + ... + \alpha p.x[t-p] + \beta 1. w[t-1] + \beta 2. w[t-2] + ... + \beta q. w[t-q]\]

where \({w[t]}\) is white noise. Note that \(AP(p)\) is \(ARMA(p,0)\). Often, an \(ARMA( p,q)\) requires (far) fewer parameters than pure AR or MA processes would.

Clearly, A time series \({x[t]}\) follows an \(ARIMA(p, d, q)\) process if the dth differences of the ${x[t]} series are an \(ARMA(p, q)\) process.

In fitting ARIMA model, the idea of parsimony is important in which the model should have as small parameters as possible yet still be capable of explaining the series (p and q should be 2 or less, or the total number of parameters should be less than 3 in view of Box-Jenkins method4). The more parameters the greater noise that can be introduced into the model and hence standard deviation

We can use the AIC result to determine the appropriate ARIMA model (usually choose the smallest AIC model)

Below is the code of several different arima() model functions for fitting the data and calculate the AIC result.

ARCH model

Sometimes the series will exhibits periods of increased variability, sometimes called \(volatility\). In order to account for volatility, we require a model that allows for conditional changes in the variance. One approach to this is to use an autoregressive model for the variance process. This leads to the ARCH(1) model, which considers the first-order autoregressive conditional heteroskedastic.

In R, we need to use the garch() function for ARCH model, and we need the library(tseries)

Recall the \(ARIMA(1,1,1)\) model we have just used.

AAPL.arima_111 <- arima(log(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.ts), order=c(1,1,1), seas=list(order=c(0,0,0),12))
AAPL.arima_111.res <- resid(AAPL.arima_111)
acf(AAPL.arima_111.res, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1), lag.max = 20)

acf(AAPL.arima_111.res^2, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1), lag.max = 20)

There is clear evidence of volatility since the squared residuals are correlated at some lags. Hence, a GARCH model is fitted to the residual series

library(tseries) # need this library for garch() method
AAPL.garch <- garch(AAPL.arima_111.res, trace =F)
AAPL.garch.res <- resid(AAPL.garch)[-1]
acf(AAPL.garch.res, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1), lag.max=20)

acf(AAPL.garch.res^2, na.action=na.pass, ylim=c(-1,1), lag.max = 20)

Comparing the correlogram plots of ARIMA model and ARCH model, we can see that the ARCH mode performs better.

Prediction

One of the principal goals with time series analysis is to produce predictions which show the future evolution of the data. This is what it is: an extrapolation in the time domain. And this is extremely important for finance. This is the main work for most stock traders at Wall street. And as we all know, extrapolation is always (at least slightly) problematic and can lead to false conclusions. Of course, this is no different with time series forecasting.

Here, we can perform some prediction based on the models we have got from the modeling section.

First,let us try the forcast based on the model \(AR(1)\)

last_five_data <- window(AAPL_monthly_last_six_data.ts, start=c(2010,1),end=c(2014,12))
fit <- ar.burg(last_five_data, order=1)
forecast <- predict(fit, n.ahead=12)
plot(AAPL_monthly_last_six_data.ts, lty=3, col="blue", main="forcast based on AR(1)", ylab="Adj.Close price", xlab="Time")
lines(last_five_data, lwd=2, col="green")
lines(forecast$pred, lwd=2, col="red")
lines(forecast$pred+forecast$se*1.96, col="red")
lines(forecast$pred-forecast$se*1.96, col="red")

As we can see, comparing the real trend and prediction region, the model doesn’t work very well.

Also we can try the model \(AR(12)\)

last_five_data <- window(AAPL_monthly_last_six_data.ts, start=c(2010,1),end=c(2014,12))

Similarly, model \(AR(12)\) doesn’t predict very well. It is kind of dispointed at this moment, after we have spent so many time to learn the previous models. However, it should make sense that the prediction is hard, otherwise everyone can easily make money from the stock market.

Finally let us try the ARIMA model. Before the prediction, I would like to introduce a simple function that can find the appropriate ARIMA model. Recall that in the modeling section, we just edit the command on each trial and find the smallest AIC model. Here, I introduce this function, which is in the book “Introductory Time Series with R”. This approach works better when the conditional sum of squares method CSS is selected in the arima function, as the algorithm is more robust.

get.best.arima <- function(x.ts, maxord = c(1,1,1,1,1,1))
{
  best.aic <- 1e8
  n <- length(x.ts)
  for (p in 0:maxord[1]) for(d in 0:maxord[2]) for(q in 0:maxord[3])
    for (P in 0:maxord[4]) for(D in 0:maxord[5]) for(Q in 0:maxord[6])
    {
      fit <- arima(x.ts, order = c(p,d,q),
                   seas = list(order = c(P,D,Q),
                               frequency(x.ts)), method = "CSS")
      fit.aic <- -2 * fit$loglik + (log(n) + 1) * length(fit$coef)
      if (fit.aic < best.aic)
      {
        best.aic <- fit.aic
        best.fit <- fit
        best.model <- c(p,d,q,P,D,Q)
      }
    }
  list(best.aic, best.fit, best.model)
}

With this method, we can find the appropriate ARIMA parameters and then perform the prediction.

best.arima.AAPL <- get.best.arima(AAPL_monthly_last_five_data.log.ts, maxord =c(2,2,2,1,1,1))
best.fit.AAPL <- best.arima.AAPL[[2]]
acf(resid(best.fit.AAPL))

best.arima.AAPL[[3]]
## [1] 1 1 1 0 0 0

By setting different maxord(), we can get different ARIMA parameters.

\[(2,2,2,1,1,1) => 1 1 1 0 0 0\] \[(2,2,2,2,1,1) => 2 1 2 2 0 1\]

Let us use the (1,1,1,0,0,0) model to perform the prediction.

last_five_data <- window(AAPL_monthly_last_six_data.ts, start=c(2010,1),end=c(2014,12))
fit <- best.fit.AAPL
forecast <- predict(fit, n.ahead=12)
plot(AAPL_monthly_last_six_data.ts, lty=3, col="blue", main="forcast based on ARMA(1,1)", ylab="Adj.Close price", xlab="Time")
lines(last_five_data, lwd=2, col="green")
lines(exp(forecast$pred), lwd=2, col="red")
lines(exp(forecast$pred+forecast$se*1.96), col="red")
lines(exp(forecast$pred-forecast$se*1.96), col="red")

From the result, we can see this is a little bit better than other models.

Machine Learning Based Modeling & Prediction

We study the stock data in two aspects, classification and regression. For example, predicting the exact price of a stock is a regression problem, whereas predicting the trend labeled by UP or DOWN is a classification process.

Actually, predicting the exact price of a stock is super hard. Predicting the trend is also a very hard problem. Because the whole stock market is a huge dynamic system, which changes uncertainly with time. People are researching the stock market to find better models and methods for many years. Sometimes, these models or methods do not work properly because of the complexity of the stock market. But, interestingly, the finance industry always focuses on the future rather than dwell on the past.

Machine learning is a theory to study the historic data, train a descriptive mode and predict the future data. Powered by machine learning techniques, we can find something interesting in the past and give some indication for future decision.

Feature Selection

The raw data from Yahoo finance is like below:

tail(apple.stock)
##            Date   Open   High    Low  Close   Volume Adj.Close
## 6526 2015-11-20 119.20 119.92 118.85 119.30 34287100    119.30
## 6527 2015-11-23 119.27 119.73 117.34 117.75 32482500    117.75
## 6528 2015-11-24 117.33 119.35 117.12 118.88 42803200    118.88
## 6529 2015-11-25 119.21 119.23 117.92 118.03 21388300    118.03
## 6530 2015-11-27 118.29 118.41 117.60 117.81 13023700    117.81
## 6531 2015-11-30 117.99 119.41 117.75 118.30 37658700    118.30

First, we do some data cleaning (or say preparation), i.e., mark the time series (the Date) as integers, and give each attribute a name as features.

Date Open High Low Close Volume Adj Close
\(n\) \(r\) \(s\) \(t\) \(u\) \(v\) \(w\)

Then we design the groundtruth. For regression problem to fit the price, we just use the Close value \(u\) as \(y\). For the classification problem to predict the trend, use \(u_n - u_{n-1} \ge 0\) as UP else as DOWN.

Date | Price | Regression Label | Classification Label :——–:|:——:|:—————-:|:——————-: \(n\) | \(u\) | \(y = u\) | \(Y = u_n - u_{n-1} \ge 0\)? 6528 | 118.88 | 118.88 | UP 6529 | 118.03 | 118.03 | DOWN 6530 | 117.81 | 117.81 | DOWN 6530 | 118.30 | 118.30 | UP

Additionally, we combine the raw data in any reasonable ways to make more features. Because sometimes the raw data is not fully intuitive to represent the problem. And it is easy to construct new features from existed features to increase the complexity of our prediction model. So our final feature vectors are like this:

\[\left( Y, y, r, s, t, u, v, w, u^2, u^3 \dots u^6, v^2, v^3 \dots v^6, u^m v^n, u-r, s-t, (s-r)/r, (t-r)/r, (u-r)/r \right)\]

Here \(m, n \le 6\) are the orders of \(u\) and \(v\). Usually, the trend of Price \(u\) is opposite to the trade Volume \(v\). So calculating \(u^m v^n\) is to find some correlation between the two variables. Intuitively, \(u-r\) means the difference between two dates, and \(s-t\) means what is the maximum of range in one date. \((s-r)/r, (t-r)/r\), and similarly \((u-r)/r\) are the relative amplitudes compared with the Open price in a date.

Experiments

We take the experiments on the stock of Apple Inc. during the past 25 years, starting 1990-01-01 to 2015-11-30, totally 6531 daily examples, sampled monthly 311 examples. Totually, 52% of the data is positive data.. A set of machine learning algorithms are applied to both the raw and the feature-selected datasets on daily and monthly basis. The chosen machine learning algorithms for classification are Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression, KNN, AdaBoost, Bagging, Decision Trees, RandomForests, while for regression are linear regression. Then we have the prediction rate of each algorithm and compare the results.

From the results, we found that:

  • Our well-designed features are very good for modeling the stock price, for both classification and regression. The classification rate can be achieved by most algorithms we use. And the . On the whole, it performs much better than the raw data.

  • The prediction rate of monthly data is usually better than the one of daily base. That makes sense. One reason is that the monthly data is much smaller than the daily. The second reason is that the stock waves more drastically in the daily basis.

  • For our feature-seleted data, Logistic Regression, KNN, Adaboost, Bagging, Decision Trees and Random Forests have good prediction rates. Only Naive Bayes performs bad. The reason is that Naive Bayes is based on conditional independence and perform very poor on outliers. From the Apple’s stock plot, we’ve already found that there are two times that the stock price wave too much during the economic crisis in 2008 and the recession of performance Iphone 5 product in 2012 (when were competed by Samsung in that year).

In conclusion, we can see the machine learning algorithms do help on the problems of stock prediction, both the stock price prediction and the trend prediction.

Summary & Conclusion

We have studied the time series data modeling topic by looking at stock price in two ways. One is the traditional time series modeling. We have explored several different time series models and applied them on the stock price modeling and prediction. The other is the machine learning techniques. Time series modeling is to model the data first and then predict the data. On the contrary, machine learning techniques are in a computational manner, which is not to modeling at first.

In the process of this course project, we have learned how to doing data science to real world problem.
